url_mine = r'https://github.com/WangAline/projet_VE/raw/main/image_mine.jpg'
resp = requests.get(url_mine, stream=True).raw
image_array_mine = np.asarray(bytearray(resp.read()), dtype="uint8")
print(f'Shape of the image {image_array_mine.shape}')
image_mine = cv2.imdecode(image_array_mine, cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)
plt.axis('off')
plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(image_mine, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
plt.show()

In[5]:
# Download ZIP file
data_dir = tf.keras.utils.get_file(
    "dataset.zip",
    "https://github.com/WangAline/projet_VE/raw/main/dataset/dataset.zip",
    extract=False
)

# Extract ZIP file
with zipfile.ZipFile(data_dir, 'r') as zip_ref:
    zip_ref.extractall('/content/datasets')

# Definition of extracted data path
data_dir = pathlib.Path('/content/datasets/dataset')

# Path display
print(data_dir)
print(os.path.abspath(data_dir))

In[6]:
batch_size = 16
image_heigth=300
image_width=300

These variables define key parameters for training the model:

  1. batch_size = 16: Number of images processed at the same time. A small batch reduces memory but can make the optimisation less stable.
  2. image_height = 300 and image_width = 300: Image resizing dimensions before training. Used to standardise the size of model inputs.

Calculation of iterations per epoch If you choose a batch size of 16 :

Number of batches per epoch : 300/16=19

This means that for each epoch, 19 iterations will be required to process the entire dataset.

Building the model

The layers module of tensorflow.keras contains a wide range of layers that can be used to build a neural network model in TensorFlow/Keras. These layers are the basic elements which define the structure of the model.

In[12]:
from tensorflow.keras import layers
In[20]:
num_classes = 2

model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.Rescaling(1./255),
    layers.Conv2D(128,4, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Conv2D(64,4, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Conv2D(32,4, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Conv2D(16,4, activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D(),
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(64,activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax')

])
In[21]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=tf.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
  metrics=['accuracy'],)

logdir="logs"

tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(
    log_dir=logdir,
    histogram_freq=1,
    write_images=True
)

The code creates a convolutional neural network model to classify images into two categories (mines and no mines). It normalizes the images, applies convolution and pooling layers to extract features, then flattens them before passing them to dense layers. The model is compiled with the Adam optimizer and the SparseCategoricalCrossentropy loss function. A TensorBoard callback is configured to visualise the training.

In[25]:
from google.colab import files
import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Loading the file for prediction
file_to_predict = files.upload()

for file_ in file_to_predict:
    # Read the colour image
    image_to_predict = cv2.imread(file_, cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)

    # Display the loaded image
    plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(image_to_predict, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
    plt.show()

    # Preparing the image for the model
    img_to_predict = np.expand_dims(cv2.resize(image_to_predict, (300, 300)), axis=0)

    # Use model.predict and np.argmax for prediction
    predictions = model.predict(img_to_predict)
    res = np.argmax(predictions, axis=-1)[0]  # Classe prdite (0 ou 1)

    # Displaying results
    print("Probabilits de chaque classe:", predictions)
    print("Classe prdite:", res)

    # Display the corresponding result
    print(class_names[res])
    if class_names[res] == 'Mines':
      plt.show()
      print("Mines!")
    else:
      plt.show()
      print("No Mine!")
